fields.title: Calculating the Degree Distribution of a Graph
fields.abstract: The degree of a node is simply the number of neighbors. There has been substantial computational biology research into a node's degree and the importance of that node in the network -- nodes with large degree, or hubs, often serve as critical nodes and dramatically affect the network if they are removed. fields.content_md:
# Calculating the Degree Distribution of a Graph

The **degree** of a node is simply the number of neighbors.  There has been substantial computational biology research into a node's degree and the importance of that node in the network -- nodes with large degree, or _hubs_, often serve as critical nodes and dramatically affect the network if they are removed.  In this tutorial, we will learn how to use the distribution of node degrees to better understand the global structure of a network.

## Degree Distribution

Every node in a graph has a degree. If there are _n_ nodes in a graph, then a node's degree can range from 0 (a _singleton_ node not connected to anything) to _n-1_ (a node connected to all other nodes in the graph).  The **degree distribution** is a histogram the degrees for all _n_ nodes in the graph.  This is an empirically derived distribution, but sometimes the shape of this histogram follows known probability distributions.

## What can the Degree Distribution tell us?

The shape of the degree distribution can tell us _how_ nodes tend to be connected to other nodes in the network, on a global scale.  Here, we mention two types of networks that have dramatically different degree distributions.

Suppose we have a network where the connections are randomly assigned, essentially avoiding any explicit structure in the graph.  Then, on average, each node will have about the same degree.  This simple graph model is known as the Erdos-Renyi random graph model, and the degree distribution will follow a Gaussian distribution.

![Uniformly Random Model](random-graph.png)

Now, suppose we have another network, where there are only a few nodes with large degree while the remaining nodes have very small degree.  This graph, unlike the random graph above, has a lot of structure.  Such a graph can be randomly generated using a model known as the Barabasi-Albert random graph model, which is built using the notion of "preferential attachment," where edges tend to connect singleton nodes to high-degree nodes.  Here, the degree distribution will follow a power-law distribution.

![Preferential Attachment Model](pref-attach.png)

Calculating the degree distributions can tell us whether the neIt turns out that many real-world networks look more like the structured network than the unstructured network.  These networks have been coined "scale-free", though their empirical distributions may not exactly follow a power-law distribution.

## Calculating the Degree Distribution
